I came here for the exact same request. For me the mime_type is video, but the cause is the same. Currently the `.from_template()` method checks whether the template is a) a string, or a dict that contains key `"text"` b) a dict that contains key `"image_url"`. ([langchain_core/prompts/chat.py](https://github.com/langchain-ai/langchain/blob/d9a069c414a321e7a3f3638a32ecf8a37ec2d188/libs/core/langchain_core/prompts/chat.py#L526-L536))

```python
def from_template(cls, ...):
      ...
      if isinstance(template, str):
          ...
      elif isinstance(template, list):
          for tmpl in template:
              if isinstance(tmpl, str) or isinstance(tmpl, dict) and "text" in tmpl:
                  ...
              elif isinstance(tmpl, dict) and "image_url" in tmpl:
                  ...
              else:
                  msg = f"Invalid template: {tmpl}"
                  raise ValueError(msg)                 
```

While this covers the most cases for multimodal inputs, the official how-to of google generative ai (and vertex ai) states that it should use a dict containing `"type": "media"`. (Can't find the relevant doc right now, but here's one for js - [tool_calls_multimodal#google-generative-ai](https://js.langchain.com/docs/how_to/tool_calls_multimodal/#google-generative-ai)).

I can see that the exact parameters may be model specific, but there is no way to expand the template format for such models. I lose the whole point of using templates.

